        President Hoover created the Veterans Administration (VA) in 1930 to consolidate all 
        veteran services. General Omar N. Bradley was appointed to VA administrator and Bradley
        appointed Major General Paul Hawley as director of VA medicine, both in 1945. Hawley
        successfully established a policy that affiliated new VA hospitals with medical schools.
        Hawley also promoted resident and teaching fellowships at VA hospitals. Ultimately,
        Hawley was responsible for starting the hospital-based research program at the VA. 
